All of these mount the fan at an angle or use 25 or 40 mm miniature fans. I wanted a more optimal solution so I made a fan mount that replaces the original wooden side parts of the extruder assembly. The new parts make it possible to mount a 50 mm fan right in front of the extruder for maximum cooling.
After having installed the fan I have had no more problems with sticking fillament.

Quick and easy removal and replacement of heated bed glass between prints saving time on cooling and cleaning. Purchase an oversized piece of borosilicate glass, print some parts, add springs, aluminum rod and epoxy to give affordable heated bed glass swapping. Below is a link of a video with it in use. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aWsU1yATn5U

I used four printed parts, four compression springs from a home depot assortment (4$), 1/4" Aluminum rod HD (6$), Loctite plastic epoxy HD (5$), and the 1/4"x9"x9" borosilicate glass was 25$ from McMaster-Carr.
The design is simple. It just two angled surfaces that hold the plate down and stop it from sliding. The front piece is hinged so that it can easily be removed and also hold different plate thicknesses. The hardest part of its assembly was epoxying the parts on the Da Vinci bed. I used the new glass to align the back piece while it cured then with a smaller flat piece for the front. The aluminum pin and springs just slide in.

description.text: I made a hotend you can drill from a template. Print out the template, wrap it around a metal rod, and drill where you see the holes. The design uses a Bowden cable as an isolator, so only the metal part requires drilling. Detailed instructions can be found here. Adapters are available for a number of mounting styles and printer models. Where possible, adapters are designed with optional fan mounts, which are highly recommended. An all metal variant is also available - more information is provided in the instructions.

Version 3 of the hotend returns to the monolithic design of version 1. Version 2 offered a number of improvements to the ease manufacture, however I found the lifetime of the nozzle to be significantly reduced.
Version 3 sees an overall reduction to component size. This offers a number of benefits. Smaller rods are cheaper to purchase and easier to machine. Smaller screws conduct less heat, making them less likely to melt the plastic that supports them. A smaller hotend overall has a smaller melt zone and is quicker to heat.

• 3/8" aluminum rod
  • Machine screws or threaded rod, size M3 (4-40) or M2(2-56) (longer, thinner screws work better)
  • Teflon Bowden cable, 2mm ID, 4mm OD
  • Honeywell 100K Thermistor
  • 5.6 or 6.8 Ohm vitreous resistor

• Drill
  • Taps
  • Hacksaw

Download and print "heatblock.stl". Wrap the print out around a 3/8" (9mm) metal rod. I recommend filing down the sides of your rod before you do so - it helps when drilling your holes, but it isn't strictly necessary. I prefer aluminum - it's cheap, easy to drill, and it conducts heat well. Drill anywhere you see a hole. You'll want the finished piece to match the diagram, below. The size of your drill bit should roughly fit the size of the hole. When drilling the heat resistor, start by drilling a 1/8" (M3) guidehole, then finish off with a 13/64" (M5). For other holes, check the table for recommended bit sizes. Using a tap, cut the threads into the holes that run through the top of the heat block. Again, check the table above for recommended tap sizes. Now, take a hacksaw and cut off your piece from the metal rod. There's a groove in the template that's meant for this purpose. File down the sides at the bottom of the nozzle. Drill a small (0.1-1mm) hole through the tip of the nozzle. A dremel works best for large (>0.8mm) nozzles. Smaller nozzles may require a jeweler's drill. Screw the Bowden cable onto the heatblock. Insert the heat resistor, thermistor, and Bowden cable. The Bowden cable should go all the way through the heat block and leave a few millimeters available on the other end. This will provide something with which we can attach the acorn nut. How you mount your hotend will depend on your setup. Printable adapters are provided for Jhead, Prusa i3, and Huxley style mounts. Print out whichever is most appropriate and attach it to the heat block using two long (>50mm) M3 (4-40) screws or threaded rods. I prefer stainless steel threaded rod due to its length and low thermal conductivity. These screws will also serve to secure the electronic components you inserted from earlier. the teflon tubing you installed earlier should pass through the center of the adapter and hook up with the bowden cable coupler (not shown in image below). This will allow you to easily attach and detach your hotend to the bowden cable.

When printing very high prints, sometimes the "not-so-often-used" parts of z axis rods get dusty and cause skipping.
This is designed to increase the belt-pulley contact and thus increase the friction -> less skipping. Designed to use the 623 bearings (the same as mendel inspired lowrider by twotimes.) Even when this is in place I recommend to oil the rods regularly with some gun/sewing machine oil. This too helps reduce skipping.

Print all the parts (you'll need 2 of washer.stl's)
Loosen the belt
Unscrew the bolts from stepper
Insert the m3x20 screws
Wiggle the bearings in placewith the belt in between.
Insert printed washers
Tighten the stepper bolts (make sure the hole is centered)
Put the top on and tighten the nuts
Print very high prints with reduced skipping..

description.text:
Air foils. I put two in here, primarily in the \"print and be amused\" category, but there are some legitimate tests one might try with these:
  • Mirror the hollow wing and glue them to a lasercut balsa fuselage to see if they work at all.
  • Stretch some kind of airtight fabric over the frame, clip to balsa fuselage and see if it flies.
    • However, I must advise that anything printed in a ten-centimeter cube is going to be fighting the square-cube law pretty heavily, so even my nigh-gossamer wingfoil may just not be able to get up lift.

description.text: This portable coat and purse hook follows the basic C-clamp mechanism to safely secure your purse and coat to any table up to 1.75in thick. Its small design (about 5in tall and 3.5in wide) means you can store it easily and take it with you wherever you go. The clamping mechanism makes sure the hook is secure to the table and canâ€™t be accidentally knocked off or easily stolen. Some more difficult assembly is required.

Iâ€™ve uploaded the Rhino, STL, and Gcode files along with a couple of pictures to help explain the process.
You will need:
-Safety glasses
-Jewlerâ€™s saw frame and blade
-Proper ventilation
-Epoxy
-Drill press/flex-shaft/hand drill
-#22 drill bit
-Soldering iron
  • 3 M4 nuts, .70 pitch
    -1 M4x45 bolt, .70 pitch, fully threaded. At least 2in. head not important
    1.) Download the file. Here are the print settings I used:
    2.) Print the pieces. You will want to print the hook separately from the end caps, or else you wonâ€™t get proper adhesion in the end caps and they will lift during printing. (See pic)
    3.) Allow print to set before removing carefully from bed.
    4.) Before the print completely cools, break the supports that were created. I used the tip of a large half-round file, but anything strong and thin enough should work. (See pic)
    5.) Drill the bolt hole with a #22 bit. (See pic)
    6.) Cut off head of bolt. Try to keep the cut square to maintain the integrity of the threads.
    7.) Check that nut threads onto the cut side. If nut wonâ€™t thread, put nut on other side of bolt and revolve until the nut is sitting at the end of the cut side.
    8.) Place a nut in each of the voids and push in as far as possible. For the voids on the top cap and hook, this may not be possible yet.(See pic)
    9.) In a properly ventilated area, use hot soldering iron to heat-set nuts into place. Try to keep nuts as level as possible. If void is too small, use the iron to carefully widen the hole until the nut barely fits. If nut comes loose, carefully melt plastic around the nut with the iron to encapsulate the nut. (See pic)
    10.) Let pieces cool.
    11.) Thread the bolt into both end caps and through hook. Make sure the flat disc end cap is on the inside of the hook.
    12.) Carefully epoxy the bolt to the end cap nuts and let set. Any epoxy that bonds to metal should be fine. (See pic)
    13.) Once everything is properly set, your hook should be ready to use. Please feel free to improve my designs! Also feel free to file and sand the hook to achieve a smooth look. Look up â€œTwo-toned portable coat and purse hookâ€ to make a multicolored version.

description.text:
I decided to make my own minimalistic mount because I wanted the nozzle height exactly the same as the stock nozzle, and I wanted to retain the E3D fan shroud for proper cooling to all fins.
NOTE: This does require slight trimming of the extruder mounting plate, as well as the plastic piece that fits over the stepper motor and holds the lever.

Use at your own risk - I am not responsible for any injury or damage, etc.
Print with ABS at 100% infill. I had the best results printing the clamp with the curved side facing UP, and the mount with the curved side facing DOWN, with supports of course. You will have to drill out the through-holes a bit (intentional) and use shorter screws (available at almost any hobby shop).
Trim the aluminum mounting plate per the attached drawing. I used a Dremel with a tungsten carbide cutter and then finished with a sanding drum. Then file a notch into the plastic part that mounts to the extruder. You will see where you have to file when you go to test fit - just file where the top of the e3d would hit the plastic. I decided this was better than spacing the motor up higher than necessary.
Finally, cut the PTFE tube at an angle so it fits close to the hobbed bolt and won't let soft filament go anywhere but where it's supposed to.
Enjoy!

With the UP! in mind I added an extra half-mm or so to the height of the upper lugs to make sure it slots into the standard ports in the mobile phone holder - the result is a nice, firm connection with the mass-produced phone mount, but the tolerances with the Lego holes are what you would expect.
The Shapeways print has much better tolerances on the Lego holes - again as you would expect - but the literal height increase with the lugs mean that the fit with the phone mount is not snug; it is a little loose and needs blu-tack to reliably secure.

comments.text:
Hi scoots
(1) I imported the virtual 3D head model (.stl) into Tinkercad and used the basic modeling tools to first add a curved handle and then progressively hollow out the inside by using various curved sphere and cylinder shapes as "negative spaces" to delete material . . . while being very careful to leave adequate wall thickness for the mug.
(2) I didn't print in plastic first - but should have. Shapeways didn't scale down the measurements. It was simply my own error in measuring other mugs and scaling the head to those dimensions and then sending it off for printing before double-checking how big the physical object would actually be. title: Two-Tone Portable Coat and Purse Hook

description.text: This multicolored portable coat and purse hook follows the basic C-clamp mechanism to safely secure your purse and coat to any table up to 1.75in thick. Its small design (about 5in tall and 3.5in wide) means you can store it easily and take it with you wherever you go. The clamping mechanism makes sure the hook is secure to the table and canâ€™t be accidentally knocked off or easily stolen. Some more difficult assembly is required.

Iâ€™ve uploaded the Rhino, STL, and Gcode files along with a couple of pictures to help explain the process.
You will need:
-Safety glasses
-Jewlerâ€™s saw frame and blade
-Proper ventilation
-Epoxy
-Acetone
-Small acetone safe container
-Q-tip or small brush
  • 3 M4 nuts, .70 pitch
    -1 M4x45 bolt, .70 pitch, fully threaded. At least 2in. head not important
    -2 different colored filaments
    -Sandpaper (100-200 grit should work fine)
    -File (half-round)
    -Optional: vice/c-clamps and 2 pieces of wood at least as large as hook
    1.) Download the file. Here are the print settings I used:
    2.) Print the pieces. You will want to print the hook separately from the end caps, or else you wonâ€™t get proper adhesion in the end caps and they will lift during printing. Also, print the files labeled with an â€œaâ€ in one color, and the files labeled with a â€œbâ€ in the other color.(See pic)
    3.) Allow print to set before removing carefully from bed. You want to keep the pieces as flat as possible, so they will adhere later. If any corners lifted in the printing process, you may want to address this issue and reprint.
    4.) Before the print completely cools, break the supports that were created. I used the tip of a large half-round file, but anything strong and thin enough should work. (See pic)
    5.) Drill the bolt hole with a #22 bit. (See pic)
    6.) One side of the middle piece will be rough from the printing process. Use sandpaper to smooth out this side. In order to keep the rough side flat while sanding, hold or tape sandpaper to flat, smooth surface and put pressure on entire piece while sanding.
    7.) Prepare a clean space in a properly ventilated area, preferably near a sink. You will need the acetone, Q-tip/small brush, and acetone-safe dish for the next few steps. (See pic)
    8.) Locate two sides that will be adhered together.
    9.) Working quickly and cleanly, apply liberal amounts of acetone to one of the adhesion sides. If possible, have someone else treat the other part the same way.
    10.) Once the adhesion surface(s) are coated in a layer of acetone, quickly and carefully line up pieces and hold tightly together for 30 seconds, or until all the acetone has evaporated. You may want to practice on scrap pieces first. If full adhesion isnâ€™t achieved, either take apart, or apply more acetone to the edge, lightly squeeze and release multiple times to allow acetone to get between the two layers. Then hold again until acetone has evaporated. Be aware that the acetone will make the plastic shiny.
    11.) Repeat process to adhere third piece to first two pieces.
    12.) I clamped my hook overnight, but Iâ€™m not sure if that was necessary. When clamping, make sure to have a piece of wood on each side of the hook to evenly disburse the pressure. These pieces of wood should be at least as big as the hook.
    13.) Cut off head of bolt. Try to keep the cut square to maintain the integrity of the threads.
    14.) Check that nut threads onto the cut side. If nut wonâ€™t thread, put nut on other side of bolt and revolve until the nut is sitting at the end of the cut side.
    15.) Remove hook from clamp. Place a nut in each of the voids and push in as far as possible. For the voids on the top cap and hook, this may not be possible yet.(See pic)
    16.) In a properly ventilated area, use hot soldering iron to heat-set nuts into place. Try to keep nuts as level as possible. If the hole is too small from the supports, carefully melt until nut barely fits. If nut comes loose, use the iron to carefully melt the plastic around the nut to encapsulate the nut. (See pic)
    17.) Let pieces cool.
    18.) Thread the bolt into both end caps and through hook. Make sure the flat disc end cap is on the inside of the hook.
    19.) Carefully epoxy the bolt to the end cap nuts and let set. Any epoxy that bonds to metal should be fine. (See pic)
    20..) Once everything is properly set, your hook should be ready to use. Please feel free to improve my designs!

title: Table Leaf Hanger - Hang your leaf from the rafters!

description.text: For those of you who have a table lead that you don't have a place to store it.. How about the ceiling or the rafters?? So this "thingy" is designed to be mounted on the rafter or wall in series and then you hang your extra table leaf in it until the next holiday party you have needs the leaf!

This is built in a series of 4 hangers. Each hanger has a hole for a screw. Measure the width of the table leaf you need to hang and add an 2 inches (W+2 =n)
Measure the length of the table leaf you need to hang (L) With the rafters horizontal to you, mount the 1st set of two n apart on the same rafter
Move down about 2 rafters or x distance (L/2=x)
Mount the next set n distance apart. You may want to print and install several in series so that the weight of the leaf can be equally distributed. Now you simply slip the edge of the leaf into the 1st set of hangers on one side, push up, and slide the lead into the second side and - its HUNG. No more leaf sitting some place. I have engineered these with extra support - but have not tested max load - so enjoy at your own risk. These work great for me. NOTE: I have put a single and group of 4 for easy printing

comments.text: So I built asset of 4 of these with a 20% fill and installed them with a 22 lb table leaf. while there is a little give/flex (7mm) on the ends this is holding very well and zero fatigue. I did put a bungee cord up as a backup. I think these would also work well if you had a sheets of plywood you wanted to store on the ceiling of your garage.. I'm thinking of building a stacked set with 2x screw holes so you could put several sheets of plywood and stash them on the ceiling of your basement or in the rafters..

I loved the great design by thinkyhead for a simple geared extruder on a prusa i3. I modded it to fit two extruders (one mirrored) and use a mk8 (rather than mk7) drive gear.
To make this work, I made a few notable modifications:
  • I moved the motor over 2mm to make the hobbed gear contact the filament
  • I made the mount holes 30mm apart so it would fit a standard dual carriage that has 30-20-30 spacing.
  • I made the mount holes movable up and down to let you easily tweak the height of the extruder heads and level them
  • I got rid of the extra mounting bolt hole so you don't have to print a special carriage (it's not as stable, but a few zip ties solve this.
  • I removed the cone transition for the entrance of the filament to the hotend from the hobbed gear to reduce the chance of buckling with softer filaments.
  • Finally, I pushed the bore for the j-head mount down slightly because mine fit a little to tight for comfort.
    I also made mods for the fan mount since I was using a smaller fan. I've included the fan I use and I hate to not reference it's thing#, but I can't remember where I got it.
    I included the original tweety openscad file for reverence.
    If you use the 50:1 geared stepper motors from 2engineers.com you'll want to use a heatsink (I found one intended for the PG35L at ultibots.com and you might consider going with that motor and modifying this design for it)
    I would print everything in ABS since the motor gets pretty warm - I actually deformed the idler when I printed for a while without a heatsink.
    You'll also need to modify your firmware according to 2engineers.com to prevent damage from acceleration (in addition to enabling dual extrusion).
    enjoy

Rather than screws, I used two small zap straps to attach the factory base of the detector to my mount. Then it slips over the upper vertical post. My detector is a "Lifesaver Model i9040CA" from Canadian Tire.
The sketchup file and stl are in case anyone wants to modify it.

description.text: Pencil mount for a CNC with exchangable adapters for different pen sizes/styles.

This design can/shall be adapted for your needs but serves as a design concept for a mount where only a tiny adapter can be exchanged in order to usr different types of pencils. The inner diameter of the pipe is 16mm - so the outer dimension of the adapters needs to be slightly smaller than that. On my Up! Mini printer a radie of 0.15-0.2mm less (diameter 15.7 mm in this case) seems to be perfect for a good press fit based on my experience. Printing it upright (or even better upside down for no support needed) helps with the layers locking each other by friction between body and adapters.. You needs to print two adapters (one upper and one lower) with your own meassurements , unless you happend to have an IKEA pen :-)- Most likely you also need to take the idea and create you own design to fit your CNC. Update1:
The exchangable adapters worked great and I also did adapters in other sizes for other pens - next step is probably a spring loaded pen as "lead pencils" have a hard time to reach the paper after some lines has been drawn.... (I also tried freehanging pens and used gravity but the drawback is that it can't be lifted....) Update2:
Made my first OpenSCAD script ever to have it customizable in Thingiverse :-)
